ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Taxation_sidebar" title=3D"Template:T=
axation sidebar"><abbr title=3D"View this template">v</abbr></a></li><li cl=
ass=3D"nv-talk"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template_talk:Taxa=
tion_sidebar" title=3D"Template talk:Taxation sidebar"><abbr title=3D"Discu=
ss this template">t</abbr></a></li><li class=3D"nv-edit"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:EditPage/Template:Taxation_sidebar" title=3D=
"Special:EditPage/Template:Taxation sidebar"><abbr title=3D"Edit this templ=
ate">e</abbr></a></li></ul></div></td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>A <b>capital gains tax</b> (<b>CGT</b>) is the tax on profits realised o=
n the sale of a non-inventory <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asse=
t" title=3D"Asset">asset</a>. The most common <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Capital_gain" title=3D"Capital gain">capital gains</a> are real=
ised from the sale of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stock" title=
=3D"Stock">stocks</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bond_(finan=
ce)" title=3D"Bond (finance)">bonds</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Precious_metal" title=3D"Precious metal">precious metals</a>, <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_estate" title=3D"Real estate">real =
estate</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Property" title=3D=
"Property">property</a>.
</p><p>Not all countries impose a capital gains tax, and most have differen=
t rates of taxation for individuals compared to corporations. Countries tha=
t do not impose a capital gains tax include <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Bahrain" title=3D"Bahrain">Bahrain</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Barbados" title=3D"Barbados">Barbados</a>, <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Belize" title=3D"Belize">Belize</a>, the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cayman_Islands" title=3D"Cayman Islands">=
Cayman Islands</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isle_of_Ma=
n" title=3D"Isle of Man">Isle of Man</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_no=
te-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jamaica" title=3D=
"Jamaica">Jamaica</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-2"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_Zealand" title=3D"New Zealand"=
>New Zealand</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sri_Lanka" title=
=3D"Sri Lanka">Sri Lanka</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sing=
apore" title=3D"Singapore">Singapore</a>, and others. In some countries, su=
ch as New Zealand and Singapore, professional traders and those who trade f=
requently are taxed on such profits as a business income.
</p><p>Capital gains taxes are payable on most valuable items or assets sol=
d at a profit. Antiques, shares, precious metals and second homes could be =
all subject to the tax if the profit is large enough. This lower boundary o=
f profit is set by the government, and if the profit is lower than this lim=
it it is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tax_exemption" title=3D"T=
ax exemption">tax-free</a>. The profit is in most cases the difference betw=
een the amount (or value) an asset is sold for and the amount it was bought=
 for.
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tax_rate" title=3D"Tax =
rate">tax rate</a> on capital gains may depend on the seller's income. If a=
ny property or asset is sold at a loss, it is possible to offset it against=
 annual gains. For <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equities" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Equities">equities</a>, national and state legisl=
ation often has a large array of fiscal obligations that must be respected =
regarding capital gains.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"As_an_obstacle_to_sale">As =
an obstacle to sale</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit =
section: As an obstacle to sale"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The CGT can be considered a cost of selling which can be greater than, f=
or example, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transaction_cost" titl=
e=3D"Transaction cost">transaction costs</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Provision_(accounting)" title=3D"Provision (accounting)">prov=
isions</a>. The literature provides information that barriers for trading n=
egatively affects the investors' willingness to trade, which in turn can ch=
ange asset prices.
</p><p>Companies with tax-sensitive customers are particularly reactive to =
capital gains tax and its change. CGT and changes to it affect trading and =
the stock market. Investors must be ready to react sensibly to these change=
s, taking into account the cumulative capital gains of their customers. The=
y are sales must be delayed due to an unfavorable market conditions caused =
by capital gains tax. A study by Li Jin (2006) showed that great capital ga=
ins discourage selling. On the contrary to this fact, small capital gains s=
timulate the trade and investors are more likely to sell.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-:1_3-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capi=
tal_gains_tax#cite_note-:1-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> "It is easy to show that to be wil=
ling to sell now the investor must believe that the stock price will go dow=
n permanently. Thus, a capital gains tax can create a potentially large bar=
rier to selling. Of course, the foregoing calculation ignores the possibili=
ty that there might be another tax-timing option: Given capital gains tax r=
ates fluctuate over time, it might be worthwhile to time the realization of=
 capital gains and wait until a subsequent regime lowers the capital gains =
tax rate."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:1_3-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-:1-3"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Locked-in_effect">Locked-in=
 effect</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapi=
tal_gains_tax&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Loc=
ked-in effect"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
]</span></span></div>
<p>Because capital gains are taxed only upon realization, an individual who=
 owns a security that has increased in value may be less likely to sell it.=
 The seller knows that when sold, tax is levied on the positive difference =
of the price at which the security was bought and the price at sale. If the=
 seller chooses not to sell, the tax is postponed to later date. Postponing=
 allows more time for the security to grow in value and generate returns. I=
f the seller delays the sale, though the absolute value of the tax is great=
er than if they had not delayed, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Present_value" title=3D"Present value">present discounted value</a> of t=
he tax is reduced; thus allowing the security to grow undoes the tax. There=
fore, the seller has an incentive to hold the securities longer than they w=
ould have without capital gains tax. This distortion has been called the lo=
cked-in effect or lock-in effect.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:2_4-0" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-=
:2-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Martin_Feldstein" title=3D"=
Martin Feldstein">Martin Feldstein</a>, former chairman of the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Council_of_Economic_Advisers" title=3D"Council=
 of Economic Advisers">Council of Economic Advisers</a> under President <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ronald_Reagan" title=3D"Ronald Reagan=
">Reagan</a> has claimed that the effect is so large that reducing the capi=
tal gains tax would lead individuals to sell securities that they previousl=
y had refused to sell, to such an extent that government revenues would act=
ually increase.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=
=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikip=
edia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"Th=
is claim needs references to reliable sources. (December 2024)">citation ne=
eded</span></a></i>]</sup> 1994 estimates suggest that a permanent reductio=
n in the capital gains tax rate would have little effect.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_g=
ains_tax#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Administrative_expenses">Ad=
ministrative expenses</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.ph=
p?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edi=
t section: Administrative expenses"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>With collecting of any type of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Tax" title=3D"Tax">tax</a> come administrative costs associated with collec=
ting, administering and managing the collection of capital gains taxes. The=
se costs are directly incurred by governments that collect taxes, and ultim=
ately its citizens. Unfortunately, no studies (at least that <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fraser_Institute" title=3D"Fraser Institute">Fra=
ser Institute</a> researchers knew of in 2007) specifically analyze the cos=
ts associated with capital gains taxes.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_6-0" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite=
_note-:0-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Canadian researcher Francois Vailancourt<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#c=
ite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup> in 1989 examines the administrative costs associated=
 with personal income taxes and two payroll taxes (CPP/QPP and UI). The cos=
ts include processing costs, administration and accommodation costs, capita=
l expenses, and litigation costs. These costs represented <i><b>roughly 1% =
of the gross revenues collected</b></i> by these three tax sources. The pap=
er does not show exactly what costs are incurred by capital gains tax.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Compliance_costs">Complianc=
e costs</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapi=
tal_gains_tax&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Com=
pliance costs"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
]</span></span></div>
<p>Tax compliance costs are incurred when fulfilling the recording and fili=
ng requirements associated with paying a tax. These costs include such expe=
nses as bookkeeping, reporting, calculating, and remitting tax payments. A =
study from 1992, which may be outdated due to technological advancements, f=
ound that American taxpayers who received capital gains income incurred hig=
her compliance costs than those who did not.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite=
_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup> From a survey of 2,000 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Minnesota" title=3D"Minnesota">Minnesota</a> households, the autho=
rs found that having capital gains increased the time individuals spent on =
paying taxes by 7.9 hours, increased the money they spent on professional t=
ax assistance by about $21, and increased the total cost of compliance by $=
143 per taxpayer (not adjusted for inflation) per year.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
:0_6-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capita=
l_gains_tax#cite_note-:0-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Altogether the study concludes that very few studies measure complia=
nce costs associated with capital gains tax, but those few that do clearly =
indicate that compliance costs are not insignificant. Therefore, the costs =
must be taken into consideration when assessing tax policy.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Tax_avoidance_or_deferrence=
">Tax avoidance or deferrence</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/=
index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" titl=
e=3D"Edit section: Tax avoidance or deferrence"><span>edit</span></a><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Taxpayers may defer capital gains taxes by simply deferring the sale of =
the asset. Depending on the specifics of national tax law, taxpayers may be=
 able to legally reduce, or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tax_av=
oidance" title=3D"Tax avoidance">avoid capital gains taxes</a> using the fo=
llowing strategies:
</p>
<ul><li>A nation may tax at a lower rate the gains on investments in favore=
d industries or sectors, such as small business.</li>
<li>Tax can be reduced when property ownership is transferred to family mem=
bers in the low-income bracket. In the U.S., if in the year of selling the =
property your family member falls within the 10% to 12% ordinary income tax=
 bracket, he or she could avoid the capital gains tax entirely.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cap=
ital_gains_tax#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>There may be accounts with tax-favored status. The most advantageous of=
 these let gains accumulate in the account without taxes; however, taxes ma=
y be owed when the taxpayer withdraws funds from the account.</li>
<li>Selling an asset at a loss may create a "tax loss" that can be applied =
to offset gains realized in the future, and avoid or reduce taxes on those =
gains. Tax losses are a business asset, but the business must avoid <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tax_shelter#Judicial_doctrines_to_combat_=
tax_shelters" title=3D"Tax shelter">"sham" transactions</a>, such as sellin=
g to oneself or a subsidiary for no legitimate purpose other than to create=
 a tax loss.</li>
<li>Tax may be waived if the asset is given to a charity.</li>
<li>Tax may be deferred if the taxpayer sells the asset but receives paymen=
t from the buyer over a period of years. However, the taxpayer bears the ri=
sk of a default by the buyer during that period. A <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Structured_sale" title=3D"Structured sale">structured sale=
</a> or purchase of an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Life_annuit=
y" title=3D"Life annuity">annuity</a> may be ways to defer taxes.</li>
<li>In certain transactions, the basis (original cost) of the asset is chan=
ged. In the U.S., the basis for an inherited asset becomes its value at the=
 time of the inheritance.</li>
<li>Tax may be deferred if the seller of an asset puts the funds into the p=
urchase of a "like-kind" asset. In the U.S., this is called a <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internal_Revenue_Code_section_1031" title=3D"In=
ternal Revenue Code section 1031">1031 exchange</a> and is now generally av=
ailable only for business-related real estate and tangible property.</li>
<li>Tax may be deferred if the capital gain income is reinvested into certa=
in geographic areas. In the U.S., the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Opportunity_Zone" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Opportunity Zone">Oppo=
rtunity Zone</a> program was created to "recycle capital into the economy t=
hat would otherwise be 'frozen' in place due to investors' reluctance to tr=
igger capital gains taxes" and "bring investment and development to lower i=
ncome areas that do not otherwise receive a great deal of attention".<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Tax_evasion">Tax evasion</h=
2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_=
tax&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Tax evasion">=
<span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span>=
</div>
<p>Capital gains taxes have also led some taxpayers to illegally evade the =
payment of the tax. The level of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/T=
ax_evasion" title=3D"Tax evasion">tax evasion</a> is the extent to which ac=
tual tax revenue collected by government differs from that which would have=
 been collected if every taxpayer paid exactly what is required by law. Tax=
 evasion has important implications for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Tax_efficiency" title=3D"Tax efficiency">efficiency</a> of taxes,=
 since resources spent on evading the tax could be put to more productive u=
ses.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_6-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-:0-6"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Professor <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_M._Poterba"=
 title=3D"James M. Poterba">James Poterba's</a> work from 1987 in the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Economic_Review" title=3D"Amer=
ican Economic Review">American Economic Review</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_t=
ax#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup> studied the relationship between capital gains=
 taxes and tax evasion: a 1% decrease in capital gains tax rate increases t=
he reported tax base by 0.4% (amounting to a 0.6% decrease in tax collected=
).
</p><p>A more recent study from the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Journal_of_Public_Economics" title=3D"Journal of Public Economics">Jou=
rnal of Public Economics</a></i><sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-12"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> provides support for Poterba's work with evidence from a unique =
data set of shareholder information from the 1989 leveraged buyout of <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RJR_Nabisco" title=3D"RJR Nabisco">RJR =
Nabisco</a>. The study estimates that a one percentage-point increase in th=
e marginal tax rate on capital gains is associated with a 0.42% increase in=
 evasion (amounting to a 0.58% increase in tax collected). In addition, the=
 authors find that the average level of evasion was 11% of the total capita=
l gains.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"By_country">By country</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_ta=
x&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: By country"><sp=
an>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></d=
iv>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Albania">Albania</h3><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Albania"><span>edit</=
span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Albania" title=3D"Albania">A=
lbania</a>, capital gains on the sale of stocks or shares are taxable at 15=
%. This tax rate also applies to capital gains made from transfers of owner=
ship of real estate, both land or buildings. Individual income tax rate on =
dividends is 8%.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Argentina">Argentina</h3><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&=
amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: Argentina"><span>=
edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>There is no specific capital gains tax in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Argentina" title=3D"Argentina">Argentina</a>; however, there is =
a 9% to 35% tax for fiscal residents on their world revenues, including cap=
ital gains.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"wh=
ite-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:C=
itation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This cla=
im needs references to reliable sources. (March 2009)">citation needed</spa=
n></a></i>]</sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Australia">Australia</h3><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&=
amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: Australia"><span=
>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div=
>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article=
: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax_in_Australia" =
title=3D"Capital gains tax in Australia">Capital gains tax in Australia</a>=
</div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Australia" title=3D"Australia">=
Australia</a> collects capital gains tax only upon realized capital gains, =
except for certain provisions relating to deferred-interest <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Debt" title=3D"Debt">debt</a> such as <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zero-coupon_bond" title=3D"Zero-coupon bond">=
zero-coupon bonds</a>. The tax is not separate in its own right, but forms =
part of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Income_tax" title=3D"I=
ncome tax">income-tax</a> system. The proceeds of an asset sold less its "c=
ost base" (the original cost plus additions for cost price increases over t=
ime) are the capital gain. Discounts and other concessions apply to certain=
 taxpayers in varying circumstances. Capital gains tax is collected from as=
sets anywhere in the world, not only in Australia.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_t=
ax#cite_note-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Capital gains tax (CGT) is the levy applied to profits from selling =
your assets. Despite its designation as =E2=80=98capital gains tax,=E2=80=
=99 it is not a standalone tax but rather a constituent part of Australia=
=E2=80=99s income tax. When you sell assets (typically upon ceasing ownersh=
ip), a CGT event is triggered, and you must disclose capital gains and loss=
es in your income tax return.
</p><p>From 21 September 1999, after a report by <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Alan_Reynolds_(economist)" title=3D"Alan Reynolds (economist=
)">Alan Reynolds</a>, the 50% capital gains tax discount has been in place =
for individuals and for some trusts that acquired the asset after that time=
 and that have held the asset for more than 12 months, however the tax is l=
evied without any adjustment to the cost base for inflation. The amount lef=
t after applying the discount is added to the assessable income of the taxp=
ayer for that financial year.
</p><p>For individuals, the most significant exemption is the principal <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DFamily_home&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;redlink=3D1" class=3D"new" title=3D"Family home (page does not =
exist)">family home</a> when not used for business purposes such as rental =
income or home-based business activity. The sale of personal residential pr=
operty is normally exempt from capital gains tax, except for gains realized=
 during any period in which the property was unused as a personal residence=
 (for example, while leased to other tenants) or portions attributable to b=
usiness use. Capital gains or losses as a general rule can be disregarded f=
or CGT purposes when assets were acquired before 20 September 1985 (pre-CGT=
).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Austria">Austria</h3><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Edit section: Austria"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Austria" title=3D"Austria">Aust=
ria</a> taxes capital gains at 25% (on checking account and "Sparbuch" inte=
rest) or 27.5% (all other types of capital gains). There is an exception fo=
r capital gains from the sale of shares of foreign entities (with opaque ta=
xation) if the participation exceeds 10% and shares are held for over one y=
ear (so-called "Schachtelprivileg").<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-1=
6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Belarus">Belarus</h3><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: Belarus"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Belarus" title=3D"Belarus">B=
elarus</a>, capital gains are included in the total income of the individua=
l taxpayer. Income from the sale of one house, apartment, building, land pl=
ot, garage and a car parking space within 5 years and more is not taxable. =
However, income from the second sale and every subsequent sale of an immova=
ble property of the same type within a five-year period is fully taxable.
</p><p>Income derived from the disposal of one vehicle within a calendar ye=
ar is exempted from PIT, but is subject to PIT with standard terms for ever=
y subsequent disposal of a vehicle.
</p><p>Income derived from the disposal of shares in a statutory capital of=
 a Belarusian company is exempted from PIT as long as the taxpayer was in p=
ossession of these shares for a continuous period of no less than three yea=
rs.
</p><p>Income derived from the sale of securities is subject to PIT in comp=
liance with the Tax Code.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-17"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up>
</p><p>The capital gains tax rate in Belarus is 18% for disposal of stocks/=
shares.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Belgium">Belgium</h3><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" title=3D"Edit section: Belgium"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Under the participation exemption, capital gains realised by a Belgian r=
esident company on shares in a Belgian or foreign company are fully exempt =
from corporate income tax, provided that the dividends on the shares qualif=
y for the participation exemption. For purposes of the participation exempt=
ion for capital gains the minimum participation test is not required.
Unrealised capital gains on shares that are recognised in the financial sta=
tements (which recognition is not mandatory) are taxable. But a roll-over r=
elief is granted if, and as long as, the gain is booked in a separate reser=
ve account on the balance sheet and is not used for distribution or allocat=
ion of any kind.
</p><p>As a counterpart to the new exemption of realised capital gains, cap=
ital losses on shares, both realised and unrealised, are no longer tax dedu=
ctible. However, the loss incurred in connection with the liquidation of a =
subsidiary company remains deductible up to the amount of the paid-up share=
 capital.
</p><p>Other capital gains are taxed at the ordinary rate. If the total amo=
unt of sales is used for the purchase of depreciable fixed assets within 3 =
years, the taxation of the capital gains will be spread over the depreciabl=
e period of these assets.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-18"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Brazil">Brazil</h3><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;ac=
tion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D14" title=3D"Edit section: Brazil"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Capital gain taxes are only paid on realized gains. At the current stage=
, taxes are 15% for transactions longer than one-day-old and 20% for day tr=
ading, both transactions are due payable at the following month after selli=
ng or closing the position. Dividends are tax free, since the issuer compan=
y has already paid to <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Receita_F=
ederal_do_Brasil" title=3D"Receita Federal do Brasil">RECEITA FEDERAL</a></=
i> (the Brazilian tax office). Derivatives (futures and options) follow the=
 same rules for tax purposes as company stocks. When selling less than R$20=
.000 (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brazilian_Real" class=3D"mw-=
redirect" title=3D"Brazilian Real">Brazilian Reais</a>) within a month (and=
 not operating in day trading), the financial operation is considered tax-f=
ree. Also, non-residents have no tax on capital gains.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-B=
razilian_19-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-Brazilian-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Bulgaria">Bulgaria</h3><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&am=
p;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D15" title=3D"Edit section: Bulgaria"><span>ed=
it</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The Corporate tax rate is 10%.
The personal tax rate is flat at 10%.
There is no capital gains tax on equity instruments traded on the BSE.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Canada">Canada</h3><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;ac=
tion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D16" title=3D"Edit section: Canada"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A Capital Gains tax was first introduced in Canada by <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pierre_Trudeau" title=3D"Pierre Trudeau">Pierre Trud=
eau</a> and his finance minister <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E=
dgar_Benson" title=3D"Edgar Benson">Edgar Benson</a> in the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1971_Canadian_federal_budget" title=3D"1971 Canad=
ian federal budget">1971 Canadian federal budget</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:L=
eaderPost_20-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-:LeaderPost-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Some exceptions apply, such as selling one's primary residence which=
 may be exempt from taxation.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-21" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-21"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> Capital gains made by investments in a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Tax-Free_Savings_Account" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Tax-F=
ree Savings Account">Tax-Free Savings Account</a> (TFSA) are not taxed.
</p><p>Since the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2013_Canadian_fed=
eral_budget" title=3D"2013 Canadian federal budget">2013 budget</a>, intere=
st can no longer be claimed as a capital gain. The formula is the same for =
capital losses and these can be carried forward indefinitely to offset futu=
re years' capital gains; capital losses not used in the current year can al=
so be carried back to the previous three tax years to offset capital gains =
tax paid in those years.
</p><p>Profitable sales of assets result in either capital gains (included =
in income at a rate of 50%) or income from a business (included fully in in=
come). Characterization depends on a number of criteria, and varies based o=
n the type of assets disposed of. Sales of securities typically result in c=
apital gains, although "trading" securities with e.g. short holding periods=
, frequent transactions, or where they constitute a large share of one's in=
come suggests business income.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-22"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> In the case of other assets, sales are "income account" when they =
are purchased to be sold, particularly in a short time, whereas sales of as=
sets acquired for personal use or to generate income are on "capital accoun=
t".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-24" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_g=
ains_tax#cite_note-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>For corporations as for individuals, 50% of realized capital gains a=
re taxable. The net taxable capital gains (which can be calculated as 50% o=
f total capital gains minus 50% of total capital losses) are subject to inc=
ome tax at normal corporate tax rates. If more than 50% of a small business=
's income is derived from specified investment business activities (which i=
nclude income from capital gains) they are not permitted to claim the small=
 business deduction.
</p><p>Capital gains earned on income in a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Registered_Retirement_Savings_Plan" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D=
"Registered Retirement Savings Plan">Registered Retirement Savings Plan</a>=
 are not taxed at the time the gain is realized (i.e., when the holder sell=
s a stock that has appreciated inside of their RRSP) but they are taxed whe=
n the funds are withdrawn from the registered plan (usually after being con=
verted to a Registered Income Fund at the age of 71.) These gains are then =
taxed at the individual's full marginal rate.
</p><p>Capital gains earned on income in a TFSA are not taxed at the time t=
he gain is realized. Any money withdrawn from a TFSA, including capital gai=
ns, are also not taxed.
</p><p>Unrealized capital gains are generally not taxed, except for the dee=
med disposition when emigrating out of Canada or inheritance by a non-spous=
e.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In 2022, with price levels surging, some economists have argued that=
 the capital gain tax should be adjusted for inflation, saying that without=
 such adjustment, it taxes "fictional gains", which discourages investment.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"China">China</h3><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;acti=
on=3Dedit&amp;section=3D17" title=3D"Edit section: China"><span>edit</span>=
</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1305433154"><table class=3D"box-Unreferenced_section plainlinks metadata am=
box ambox-content ambox-Unreferenced" role=3D"presentation"><tbody><tr><td =
class=3D"mbox-image"><div class=3D"mbox-image-div"><span typeof=3D"mw:File"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Question_book-new.svg" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"icon" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.=
org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/60px-Question_book-new.sv=
g.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"50" height=3D"39" class=3D"mw-file-eleme=
nt" data-file-width=3D"512" data-file-height=3D"399"></a></span></div></td>=
<td class=3D"mbox-text"><div class=3D"mbox-text-span">This section <b>does =
not <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citing_sources" titl=
e=3D"Wikipedia:Citing sources">cite</a> any <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability" title=3D"Wikipedia:Verifiability">source=
s</a></b>.<span class=3D"hide-when-compact"> Please help <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:EditPage/Capital_gains_tax" title=3D"Special=
:EditPage/Capital gains tax">improve this section</a> by <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:Referencing_for_beginners" title=3D"Help:Refere=
ncing for beginners">adding citations to reliable sources</a>. Unsourced ma=
terial may be challenged and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikip=
edia:Verifiability#Burden_of_evidence" title=3D"Wikipedia:Verifiability">re=
moved</a>.</span>  <span class=3D"date-container"><i>(<span class=3D"date">=
May 2014</span>)</i></span><span class=3D"hide-when-compact"><i> (<small><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:Maintenance_template_removal" t=
itle=3D"Help:Maintenance template removal">Learn how and when to remove thi=
s message</a></small>)</i></span></div></td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>The applicable tax rate for capital gains in <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/China" title=3D"China">China</a> depends upon the nature of t=
he taxpayer (i.e. whether the taxpayer is a person or company) and whether =
the taxpayer is resident or non-resident for tax purposes. It should howeve=
r be noted that, unlike common law tax systems, Chinese income tax legislat=
ion does not provide a distinction between income and capital. What is comm=
only referred to by taxpayers and practitioners as capital gain tax is actu=
ally within the income tax framework, rather than a separate regime.
</p><p>Tax-resident enterprises will be taxed at 25% in accordance with the=
 Enterprise Income Tax Law. Non-resident enterprises will be taxed at 10% o=
n capital gains in accordance with the Implementing Regulations to the Ente=
rprise Income Tax Law. In practice, where a resident of a treaty partner al=
ienates assets situated in China as part of its ordinary course of business=
 the gains so derived will likely be assessed as if it is a capital gain, r=
ather than business profit. This is somewhat contradictory with the basic p=
rinciples of double taxation treaty.
</p><p>The only tax circular specifically addressing the PRC income tax tre=
atment of income derived by QFIIs from the holding and trading of Chinese s=
ecurities is Guo Shui Han (2009) No.47 ("Circular 47") issued by the State =
Administration of Taxation ("SAT") on 23 January 2009. The circular address=
es the withholding tax treatment of dividends and interest received by QFII=
s from PRC resident companies, however, circular 47 is silent on the treatm=
ent of capital gains derived by QFIIs on the trading of A-shares. It is gen=
erally accepted that Circular 47 is intentionally silent on capital gains a=
nd a possible indication that SAT is considering, but still undecided on, w=
hether to grant tax exemption or other concessionary treatment to capital g=
ains derived by QFIIs. Nevertheless, it is noted that there have been cases=
 where QFIIs withdraw capital from China after paying 10% withholding tax o=
n gains derived through share trading over the years on a transaction-by-tr=
ansaction basis. This uncertainty has caused significant problems for those=
 investment managers investing in A-Shares. Guo Shui Han (2009) No. 698 ("C=
ircular 698") was issued on 10 December 2009 addressing the PRC corporate i=
ncome tax treatment on the transfer of PRC equity interest by non-PRC tax r=
esident enterprises directly or indirectly, however has not resolved the un=
certain tax position with regards A-Shares. With respect to Circular 698 it=
self, there are views that it is not consistent with the Enterprise Income =
Tax Law as well as double taxation treaties signed by the Chinese governmen=
t. The validity of the Circular is controversial, especially in light of re=
cent developments in the international arena, such as the TPG case in Austr=
alia and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vodafone" title=3D"Vodafo=
ne">Vodafone</a> case in India.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Colombia">Colombia</h3><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&am=
p;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D18" title=3D"Edit section: Colombia"><span>ed=
it</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Under Colombian law, there are different kinds of capital gains subject =
to taxation:
</p>
<ul><li>Gains derived from the sale of assets (shares, bonds, etc.) held fo=
r a minimum of 2 years.</li>
<li>Gains derived from the liquidation of a company that has been in existe=
nce for a minimum of 2 years.</li>
<li>Gains derived from inheritances, donations or legacies (portion of esta=
te received by spouse or heir)</li>
<li>Gains derived from gambling and lotteries</li></ul>
<p>The general capital gains tax rate in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Colombia" title=3D"Colombia">Colombia</a> is 10%, with the exception=
 of lottery or gambling winnings, which are taxed at 20%.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-27" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_=
gains_tax#cite_note-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Croatia">Croatia</h3><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D19" title=3D"Edit section: Croatia"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The capital gains tax in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Croati=
a" title=3D"Croatia">Croatia</a> is 10%. It was introduced in 2015 at a rat=
e of 12% and reduced to 10% in 2021.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Cyprus">Cyprus</h3><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;ac=
tion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D20" title=3D"Edit section: Cyprus"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Capital Gains Tax (CGT) is imposed at the rate of 20% on:
</p>
<ul><li>The gains from the disposal of immovable property situated in <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cyprus" title=3D"Cyprus">Cyprus</a>.</l=
i>
<li>The gains from the disposal of shares in companies which own immovable =
property in Cyprus and that are not listed in any recognized Stock Exchange=
.</li>
<li>The gains from the disposal of shares in companies which directly or in=
directly participate in other companies which hold immovable property in Cy=
prus provided that at least 50% of the market value of the shares sold is d=
erived from property situated in Cyprus (the disposal proceeds subject to C=
GT in this case are restricted to the market value of the immovable propert=
y held directly or indirectly by the company of which the shares are sold).=
</li>
<li>Any trading nature profits derived from the sale of shares of companies=
 which directly or indirectly own immovable property in Cyprus provided tha=
t such profit is exempt from taxation under income tax.</li></ul>
<p>No CGT is imposed on the subsequent disposal of properties which are acq=
uired in the period from 17 July 2015 up to 31 December 2016.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-28" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capi=
tal_gains_tax#cite_note-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Czech_Republic">Czech Repub=
lic</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_=
gains_tax&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D21" title=3D"Edit section: Czech =
Republic"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</sp=
an></span></div>
<p>Capital gains in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Czech_Repu=
blic" title=3D"Czech Republic">Czech Republic</a> are taxed as income for c=
ompanies and individuals. The Czech income tax rate for an individual's inc=
ome in 2010 is a flat 15% rate. Corporate tax in 2024 is 21%. Capital gains=
 from the sale of shares by a company owning 10% or more is entitled to par=
ticipation exemption under certain terms. For an individual, gain from the =
sale of a primary private dwelling, held for at least 3<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
29" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_ga=
ins_tax#cite_note-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> years, is tax exempt. Or, when not used a=
s a main residence, if held for more than 5 years. Any capital gains realiz=
ed on the disposal of securities up to annual gross sale amount of <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Czech_koruna" title=3D"Czech koruna">CZK<=
/a> 100,000 are tax exempt for the taxpayer.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-30" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#c=
ite_note-30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Denmark">Denmark</h3><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D22" title=3D"Edit section: Denmark"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Share dividends and realized capital gains on shares are charged 27% to =
individuals of gains up to DKK 48,300 (2013-level, adjusted annually), and =
at 42% of gains above that.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-31" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-31"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> Carryforward of realized losses on shares is allowed.
</p><p>Individuals' interest income from bank deposits and bonds, realized =
gains on property and other capital gains are taxed up to 59%, however, sev=
eral exemptions occur, such as on selling one's principal private residence=
 or on gains on selling bonds. Interest paid on loans is deductible, althou=
gh in case the net capital income is negative, only approx. 33% tax credit =
applies.
</p><p>Companies are taxed at 25%. Share dividends are taxed at 28%.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Ecuador">Ecuador</h3><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D23" title=3D"Edit section: Ecuador"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1305433154"><table class=3D"box-Unreferenced_section plainlinks metadata am=
box ambox-content ambox-Unreferenced" role=3D"presentation"><tbody><tr><td =
class=3D"mbox-image"><div class=3D"mbox-image-div"><span typeof=3D"mw:File"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Question_book-new.svg" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"icon" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.=
org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/60px-Question_book-new.sv=
g.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"50" height=3D"39" class=3D"mw-file-eleme=
nt" data-file-width=3D"512" data-file-height=3D"399"></a></span></div></td>=
<td class=3D"mbox-text"><div class=3D"mbox-text-span">This section <b>does =
not <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citing_sources" titl=
e=3D"Wikipedia:Citing sources">cite</a> any <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability" title=3D"Wikipedia:Verifiability">source=
s</a></b>.<span class=3D"hide-when-compact"> Please help <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:EditPage/Capital_gains_tax" title=3D"Special=
:EditPage/Capital gains tax">improve this section</a> by <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:Referencing_for_beginners" title=3D"Help:Refere=
ncing for beginners">adding citations to reliable sources</a>. Unsourced ma=
terial may be challenged and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikip=
edia:Verifiability#Burden_of_evidence" title=3D"Wikipedia:Verifiability">re=
moved</a>.</span>  <span class=3D"date-container"><i>(<span class=3D"date">=
May 2014</span>)</i></span><span class=3D"hide-when-compact"><i> (<small><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:Maintenance_template_removal" t=
itle=3D"Help:Maintenance template removal">Learn how and when to remove thi=
s message</a></small>)</i></span></div></td></tr></tbody></table>
<p><b>Corporate taxation:</b>
</p><p>Residence for tax purposes is based on the place of incorporation.
</p><p>Resident entities are taxed on worldwide income. Nonresidents are su=
bject to tax only on Ecuador-source income.
</p><p>Capital gains are treated as ordinary income and taxed at the normal=
 corporate rate.
</p><p>The standard rate is 22%, with a reduced rate of 15% applying where =
corporate profits are reinvested for the purchase of machinery or equipment=
 and/or the acquisition of new technology. Companies engaged in the explora=
tion or exploitation of hydrocarbon also are subject to the standard corpor=
ate tax rate.
</p><p><b>Personal taxation:</b>
</p><p>Resident individuals are taxed on their worldwide income; nonresiden=
ts are taxed only on Ecuadorian-source income.
</p><p>An individual is deemed to be resident if they are in <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ecuador" title=3D"Ecuador">Ecuador</a> for more =
than 6 months in a year.
</p><p>Capital gains are treated as ordinary income and taxed at the normal=
 rate.
</p><p>Rates are progressive from 0% to 35%.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Egypt">Egypt</h3><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;acti=
on=3Dedit&amp;section=3D24" title=3D"Edit section: Egypt"><span>edit</span>=
</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>After the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Egyptian_Revolution_o=
f_2011" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Egyptian Revolution of 2011">Egyptia=
n Revolution</a>, there was a proposal for a 10% capital gains tax.
This proposal was implemented on 29 May 2014.
Egypt exempt bonus shares from a new 10 percent capital gains tax on profit=
s made on the stock market as the country's Finance Minister Hany Dimian sa=
id on 30 May 2014, and distributions of bonus shares will be exempt from th=
e taxes, and the new tax will not be retroactive.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-32" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_ta=
x#cite_note-32"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Estonia">Estonia</h3><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D25" title=3D"Edit section: Estonia"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>There is no separate capital gains tax in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Estonia" title=3D"Estonia">Estonia</a>. For residents of Estonia=
 all capital gains are taxed the same as regular income, the rate of which =
currently stands at 20%. Resident natural persons that have investment acco=
unt can realise capital gains on some classes of assets tax free until with=
drawal of funds from the investment account. For resident legal persons (in=
cludes partnerships) no tax is payable for realising capital gain (or recei=
ving any other type of income), but only on payment of dividends, payments =
from capital (exceeding contributions to capital) and payments not related =
to business. The income tax rate for resident legal persons is 20% (payment=
 of 80 units of dividends triggers 20 units of tax due).
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Finland">Finland</h3><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D26" title=3D"Edit section: Finland"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The capital gains tax in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Finlan=
d" title=3D"Finland">Finland</a> is 30% on realized capital income and 34% =
if the realized capital income is over 30,000 euros.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-33"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains=
_tax#cite_note-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The capital gains tax in 2011 was 28% on rea=
lized capital income.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-34" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-34"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 Carryforward of realized losses is allowed for five years. However, capita=
l gains from the sale of residential homes is tax-free after two years of r=
esidence, with certain limitations.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-35" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-35=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup>
</p><p>Dividends from a publicly listed company are 85% taxable resulting i=
n the CGT rate to be 25,5% or 28,9%. The company distributing the dividend =
will apply a 25,5% withholding tax.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-36" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-36=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"France">France</h3><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;ac=
tion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D27" title=3D"Edit section: France"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
