/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:Referencing_for_beginners" title=3D"Help:Refere=
ncing for beginners">adding citations to reliable sources</a>. Unsourced ma=
terial may be challenged and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikip=
edia:Verifiability#Burden_of_evidence" title=3D"Wikipedia:Verifiability">re=
moved</a>.</span>  <span class=3D"date-container"><i>(<span class=3D"date">=
May 2014</span>)</i></span><span class=3D"hide-when-compact"><i> (<small><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:Maintenance_template_removal" t=
itle=3D"Help:Maintenance template removal">Learn how and when to remove thi=
s message</a></small>)</i></span></div></td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>In January 2009, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Germany" title=
=3D"Germany">Germany</a> introduced a very strict capital gains tax (called=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flat_rate_withholding_tax_(Abgelt=
ungsteuer)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Flat rate withholding tax (Abgel=
tungsteuer)">Abgeltungsteuer</a> in German) for shares, funds, certificates=
, bank interest rates etc. Capital gains tax only applies to financial inst=
ruments (shares, bonds etc.) that have been bought after 31 December 2008. =
Instruments bought before this date are exempt from capital gains tax (assu=
ming that they have been held for at least 12 months), even if they are sol=
d in 2009 or later, barring a change of law. Certificates are treated speci=
ally, and only qualify for tax exemption if they have been bought before 15=
 March 2007.
</p><p>Real estate continues to be exempt from capital gains tax if it has =
been held for more than ten years.
The German capital gains tax is 25% plus <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Taxation_in_Germany#Solidarity_surcharge" title=3D"Taxation in Germa=
ny">Solidarity surcharge</a> (add-on tax initially introduced to finance th=
e five eastern states of Germany =E2=80=93 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Mecklenburg-Vorpommern" title=3D"Mecklenburg-Vorpommern">Mecklenbu=
rg-Western Pomerania</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saxony" =
title=3D"Saxony">Saxony</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saxon=
y-Anhalt" title=3D"Saxony-Anhalt">Saxony-Anhalt</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Thuringia" title=3D"Thuringia">Thuringia</a> and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brandenburg" title=3D"Brandenburg">Brande=
nburg</a> =E2=80=93 and the cost of the reunification, but later kept to fi=
nance all kinds of public funded projects in all Germany), plus <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kirchensteuer" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D=
"Kirchensteuer">Kirchensteuer</a> (church tax, voluntarily), resulting in a=
n effective tax rate of about 26.4=E2=80=9329%.
Deductions of expenses such as custodian fees, travel to annual shareholder=
 meetings, legal and tax advice, interest paid on loans to buy shares, etc.=
, are no longer permitted starting in 2009.
</p><p>There is an allowance (Freistellungsauftrag) on capital gains income=
 in Germany of =E2=82=AC1000 per person per year of which you do not have t=
o be taxed, if appropriate forms are completed.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Greece">Greece</h3><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;ac=
tion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D29" title=3D"Edit section: Greece"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Transfer of non-listed shares is subject to capital gain tax at the rate=
 of 15%. Transfer of listed shares is also taxed at 15% unless specific con=
ditions/exemptions apply. A transfer duty of 2=E2=80=B0 is imposed on the g=
ross sale proceeds of listed shares.
Other <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taxation_in_Greece" title=3D=
"Taxation in Greece">sources</a> say there is no tax in the case of capital=
 gain from trading in the stock market as long as the individual owns less =
than 0.5% of the publicly listed company.
</p><p>Dividends distributed within taxable periods commencing after 1 Janu=
ary 2020 arising from entities operating under the legal form of Soci=C3=A9=
t=C3=A9 Anonyme (or Limited Liability) are taxed via corporate withholding =
taxation at the flat rate of 5% (said rate was set to 10% for the dividends=
 distributed during the year 2019).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-37" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-37=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Hong_Kong">Hong Kong</h3><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&=
amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D30" title=3D"Edit section: Hong Kong"><span=
>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div=
>
<p>In general, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hong_Kong" title=3D=
"Hong Kong">Hong Kong</a> has no capital gains tax. However, employees who =
receive shares or options as part of their <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Remuneration" title=3D"Remuneration">remuneration</a> are taxed at=
 the normal Hong Kong income tax rate on the value of the shares or options=
 at the end of any vesting period less any amount that the individual paid =
for the grant.
</p><p>If part of the vesting period is spent outside Hong Kong, then the t=
ax payable in Hong Kong is pro-rated based on the proportion of time spent =
working in Hong Kong.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-38" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-38"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>38<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 Hong Kong has very few double tax agreements and hence there is little rel=
ief available for double taxation. Therefore, it is possible (depending on =
the country of origin) for employees moving to Hong Kong to pay full income=
 tax on vested shares in both their country of origin and in Hong Kong. Sim=
ilarly, an employee leaving Hong Kong can incur double taxation on the unre=
alized capital gains of their vested shares.
</p><p>The Hong Kong taxation of capital gains on employee shares or option=
s that are subject to a vesting period, is at odds with the treatment of un=
restricted shares or options which are free of capital gains tax.
</p><p>For those who do trading professionally (buying and selling securiti=
es frequently to obtain an income for living) as "traders", this will be co=
nsidered income subject to personal income tax rates.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Hungary">Hungary</h3><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D31" title=3D"Edit section: Hungary"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Since 1 July 2023 there are two <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Tax_rate" title=3D"Tax rate">tax rates</a> on capital income: income tax (=
15%) and social security tax (13%), adding up to 28%. This includes: sellin=
g stocks, bonds, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mutual_fund" titl=
e=3D"Mutual fund">mutual funds</a> shares and also interests from bank <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deposit_account" title=3D"Deposit acco=
unt">deposits</a>. Since January 2010, Hungarian citizens can open special =
"long-term" accounts. The tax rate on capital gains from securities held in=
 such an account is 10% after a three-year holding period, and 0% after the=
 account's maximum five years period is expired. From 1 August 2013 residen=
ts also were obligated to pay an additional 6% of health insurance tax ("EH=
O") on their capital gain. The 6% health insurance tax on capital gains was=
 abolished on 1 January 2017. On 1 July 2023, the government, citing the st=
ate of emergency in effect since the war in Ukraine, re-introduced an even =
higher 13% social security tax by decree, which was later approved by the <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parliament" title=3D"Parliament">Pa=
rliament</a> in July 2024.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-39" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-39"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Iceland">Iceland</h3><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D32" title=3D"Edit section: Iceland"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taxation_in_Iceland"=
 title=3D"Taxation in Iceland">Taxation in Iceland</a></div>
<p>From 1 January 2018 the capital gains tax in Iceland is 22%. It was 20% =
prior to that (for a full year, from 2011 to 2017), which in turn was a res=
ult of a progressive raises in the preceding years.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-40" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_=
tax#cite_note-40"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>40<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<dl><dt>Up to 2008</dt>
<dd>10%</dd>
<dt>2009 (until 30 June)</dt>
<dd>10%</dd>
<dt>2009 (from 1 July)</dt>
<dd>15%</dd>
<dt>2010</dt>
<dd>18%</dd>
<dt>2011=E2=80=932017</dt>
<dd>20%</dd>
<dt>2018</dt>
<dd>22%</dd></dl>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"India">India</h3><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;acti=
on=3Dedit&amp;section=3D33" title=3D"Edit section: India"><span>edit</span>=
</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>As of 2018, equities listed on recognised stock exchange are considered =
long term capital if the holding period is one year or more. Until 31 Janua=
ry 2017, all Long term capital gains from equities were exempt as per secti=
on 10 (38) if shares are sold through recognized stock exchange and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Securities_Transaction_Tax" title=3D"Secu=
rities Transaction Tax">Securities Transaction Tax</a> (STT) is paid on the=
 sale. STT in India is currently between 0.017% and 0.1% of total amount re=
ceived on sale of securities through a recognized Indian stock exchange lik=
e the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Stock_Exchange_of_I=
ndia" title=3D"National Stock Exchange of India">NSE</a> or <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bombay_Stock_Exchange" title=3D"Bombay Stock Exch=
ange">BSE</a>. From fiscal year 2018=E2=80=932019, exemption u/s 10(38) has=
 been withdrawn and section 112A has been introduced. The long term capital=
 gain shall be taxable on equities at 10% if the gain exceeds Rs. 100,000 a=
s per the new section.
</p><p>However, if equities are held for less than one year and is sold thr=
ough recognised stock exchange then short term capital gain is taxable at a=
 flat rate of 15% u/s 111A and other surcharges, educational cess are impos=
ed.(w.e.f. 1 April 2009.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-41" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-41"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>41<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p>)
</p><p>In respect of Immovable property, the holding period has been reduce=
d to two years to be eligible for long term capital gain. Whereas, many oth=
er capital investments like Jewellery etc. are considered long term if the =
holding period is three or more years and are taxed at 20% u/s 112.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-42" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-42"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>42<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>After 2024 changes equity sales are taxed at 12.5 percent if held fo=
r more than 1 year and 20 percent if held for less than 1 year. Indexation =
benefit from home capital gains has been removed and the tax rate has been =
bought down to 12.5 percent from 20 percent.<a rel=3D"nofollow" class=3D"ex=
ternal autonumber" href=3D"https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/budget=
-2024-capital-gains-taxes-hiked-indexation-benefit-discontinued-10172173096=
8342.html">[1]</a>
</p><p><b>Capital Gains Tax Rates for Fiscal Year 2017=E2=80=9318 (Assessme=
nt Year 2018=E2=80=9319)<sup id=3D"cite_ref-43" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-43"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p></b>
</p>
