<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Indonesia">Indonesia</h3><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&=
amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D34" title=3D"Edit section: Indonesia"><span=
>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div=
>
<p>Capital gains are generally assessable at standard income rates. The exc=
eptions are:
</p>
<ul><li>Sale of land and/or buildings located in <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Indonesia" title=3D"Indonesia">Indonesia</a>. The tax is 5% =
final tax (or 2.5% from 8 September 2016) on the taxable sale value or the =
actual proceeds, whichever is higher.</li>
<li>Sale of shares traded in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I=
ndonesia_Stock_Exchange" title=3D"Indonesia Stock Exchange">Indonesia Stock=
 Exchange</a>. The tax is 0.1% final tax on the sales proceeds.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-44" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ca=
pital_gains_tax#cite_note-44"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>44<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Ireland">Ireland</h3><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D35" title=3D"Edit section: Ireland"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Since 5 December 2012, there is a 33% tax on capital gains which general=
ly does not make any allowance for inflation.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-45" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#c=
ite_note-45"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>45<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup> There are several exclusions and deductions (e.g. =
agricultural land, primary residence, transfers between spouses). Gains mad=
e where the asset was originally purchased before 2003 attract indexation r=
elief (the cost of the asset can be multiplied by a published factor to ref=
lect inflation). Costs of purchase and sale are deductible, and every perso=
n has an exempt band of =E2=82=AC1,270 per year. Purchases made before 1 Ja=
nuary 2002 will have been in the Irish currency of the time, the Irish Punt=
. When indexing such values to present value, they firstly need to be conve=
rted to Euro by multiplying by 1.27 and then indexing to present value.
</p><p>The absence of indexation relief for transactions on assets acquired=
 since 2003 means that the headline rate of 33% is not directly comparable =
and is higher than would otherwise be the case in jurisdictions where infla=
tion is taken into account.
</p><p>The tax rate is 23% on certain investment policies, and rises to 40%=
 on certain offshore gains when they are not declared in time.
</p><p>Tax on capital gains arising in the first eleven months of the year =
must be paid by 15 December, and tax on capital gains arising in the last m=
onth of the year must be paid by the following 31 January.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Israel">Israel</h3><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;ac=
tion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D36" title=3D"Edit section: Israel"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The capital gains tax in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Israel=
" title=3D"Israel">Israel</a> is set at 25% of the real gains derived from =
the sale of securities (30% for a substantial shareholder). Non-<a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inflation-indexed_bond" title=3D"Inflation-in=
dexed bond">inflation indexed</a> bonds are taxed nominally at 15% (or 20% =
for a substantial shareholder).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-46" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-46"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>46<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Italy">Italy</h3><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;acti=
on=3Dedit&amp;section=3D37" title=3D"Edit section: Italy"><span>edit</span>=
</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Capital gains tax of corporate income tax 27.5% (IRES) on gains derived =
from disposals of participations and extraordinary capital gains. For indiv=
iduals (IRPEF), capital gains shall incur a 26% tax.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Japan">Japan</h3><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;acti=
on=3Dedit&amp;section=3D38" title=3D"Edit section: Japan"><span>edit</span>=
</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japan" title=3D"Japan">Japan=
</a>, from 1989 to 2003, there were two options for paying tax on capital g=
ains from the sale of listed stocks. The first, Withholding Tax<span style=
=3D"font-weight: normal"> (<span title=3D"Japanese-language text"><span lan=
g=3D"ja">=E6=BA=90=E6=B3=89=E8=AA=B2=E7=A8=8E</span></span>)</span>, taxed =
all proceeds (regardless of profit or loss) at 1.05%. The second method, de=
claring proceeds as "taxable income"<span style=3D"font-weight: normal"> (<=
span title=3D"Japanese-language text"><span lang=3D"ja">=E7=94=B3=E5=91=8A=
=E6=89=80=E5=BE=97</span></span>)</span>, required individuals to declare 2=
6% of proceeds on their income tax statement. Many traders in Japan used bo=
th systems, declaring profits on the Withholding Tax system and losses as t=
axable income, minimizing the amount of income tax paid.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-47" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_g=
ains_tax#cite_note-47"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>47<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In 2003, Japan scrapped the system above in favor of a flat 20% tax =
on gains, though the rate was temporarily halved at 10% and after being pos=
tponed a few times the return to the normal rate of 20% is now set for 2014=
. Losses can be carried forward for three years. Starting in 2009, losses c=
an alternatively be deducted from dividend income declared as "Separate Inc=
ome" since the tax rate on both categories is equal (i.e., 20% temporarily =
halved to 10%). Aggregating profits and dividends to reach a single figure =
taxed at the same rate is fairly innovative.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Kenya">Kenya</h3><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;acti=
on=3Dedit&amp;section=3D39" title=3D"Edit section: Kenya"><span>edit</span>=
</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Capital gains taxes were abolished in Kenya in 1985 to spur growth in th=
e securities and property market. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/National_Assembly_(Kenya)" title=3D"National Assembly (Kenya)">Kenyan P=
arliament</a> passed a motion in August 2014 to reintroduce capital gains t=
ax in January 2015<sup id=3D"cite_ref-48" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-48"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>48<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and=
 "is expected to increase the cost of land transaction as investors pass on=
 the cost to buyers. The tax will also affect those investing in shares and=
 debt in the capital markets."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-49" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-49"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> The capital gains tax came into effect on 1 January 2015 with 5% a=
s the general applicable tax rate.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-50" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-50"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>50<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Latvia">Latvia</h3><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;ac=
tion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D40" title=3D"Edit section: Latvia"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>As of 1 January 2018 the new corporate income tax act is applicable, acc=
ording to which the company's profit is taxable at a rate of 20% only upon =
the distribution of profits. In general the capital gain arising on the dis=
posal of a capital asset is treated as an ordinary income and is subject to=
 a 20% corporate income tax only, when the profit is distributed.
</p><p>A Latvian company can reduce the tax base by the capital gains the c=
ompany has earned from the sale of shares, if the Latvian company has held =
those shares for at least 36 months. If a Latvian holding company sells the=
 shares which it has owned for less than three years, the company should no=
t pay tax at the moment of the sale (but when the capital gain is distribut=
ed). However, if the company has held the shares for three years or more, t=
he company can distribute the capital gains as dividends tax-free (except, =
real estate companies).
</p><p>Personal income tax like dividends, interest and income from life in=
surance contracts and private pension funds are taxed at 10%. <a rel=3D"nof=
ollow" class=3D"external text" href=3D"https://www.liaa.gov.lv/en/invest-la=
tvia/business-guide/taxation">Capital gains</a> on the disposal of capital =
assets (such as real estate, shares and bonds) are taxed at 20%.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Lithuania">Lithuania</h3><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&=
amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D41" title=3D"Edit section: Lithuania"><span=
>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div=
>
<p>Capital gains in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lithuania" tit=
le=3D"Lithuania">Lithuania</a> are taxed as a general taxable income, there=
fore <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taxation_in_Lithuania#Persona=
l_income_tax" title=3D"Taxation in Lithuania">personal income tax</a> or <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taxation_in_Lithuania#Corporate_inco=
me_tax" title=3D"Taxation in Lithuania">corporate income tax</a> apply. As =
of 2021, 15% tax rate is applied for the disposal of securities and sale of=
 property.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-51" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-51"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>51<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-52" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ca=
pital_gains_tax#cite_note-52"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>52<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
