></span></div></td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>As of January 1, 2024, Malaysia has implemented a Capital Gains Tax (CGT=
), marking a significant shift in its tax regime. The tax applies primarily=
 to unlisted shares in Malaysian companies and foreign capital assets, with=
 specific exemptions and rates.
</p><p><b>Key Highlights:</b>
</p>
<ol><li><b>Scope of Taxation:</b>
<ul><li>CGT applies to unlisted shares in Malaysian companies and gains fro=
m foreign assets brought into Malaysia.</li>
<li>Disposals of unlisted shares between January 1 and February 29, 2024, a=
re exempt, making the effective start date March 1, 2024.</li></ul></li>
<li><b>Tax Rates:</b>
<ul><li>For assets acquired before January 1, 2024: Tax is either 10% on ch=
argeable income or 2% on the gross disposal price.</li>
<li>For assets acquired on or after January 1, 2024: Taxed at 10% of charge=
able income.</li>
<li>Gains from foreign capital assets are taxed at prevailing income tax ra=
tes when received in Malaysia.</li></ul></li>
<li><b>Filing and Compliance:</b>
<ul><li>Tax returns must be submitted electronically via the MyTax portal w=
ithin 60 days of disposal.</li>
<li>A Tax Identification Number and Digital Certificate are required for fi=
ling.</li></ul></li>
<li><b>Exemptions:</b>
<ul><li>Unit trusts are exempt from CGT and income tax on foreign-sourced i=
ncome until 2028 and 2026, respectively.</li>
<li>Real Property Gains Tax (RPGT) continues to apply separately to propert=
y transactions.</li></ul></li></ol>
<p>This move broadens Malaysia=E2=80=99s tax base and aligns with global ta=
x standards, particularly for foreign capital gains. It signifies the gover=
nment=E2=80=99s effort to enhance revenue streams while maintaining clarity=
 and exemptions for specific entities.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Mexico">Mexico</h3><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;ac=
tion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D43" title=3D"Edit section: Mexico"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>There is 10% tax rate for profits in the stock market in <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mexico" title=3D"Mexico">Mexico</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Moldova">Moldova</h3><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D44" title=3D"Edit section: Moldova"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Under the Moldovan Tax Code a capital gain is defined as the difference =
between the acquisition and the disposition price of the capital asset. Onl=
y this difference (i.e. the gain) is taxable. The applicable rate is half (=
1/2) of the income tax rate, which is 12% for individuals and companies aft=
er the changes to the tax code from 1 October 2018.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-53" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_=
tax#cite_note-53"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>53<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Thus, the current capital gains tax is 6% for=
 both individuals and companies. Earlier, between 2008 and 2011, this tax s=
tood at 0% for companies, as the corporate income tax rate has been lowered=
 to 0% to attract foreign investments and to boost the economy.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-54" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ca=
pital_gains_tax#cite_note-54"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>54<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Not all types of assets are "capital assets". Capital assets include=
: real estate; shares; stakes in limited liability companies, etc.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Montenegro">Montenegro</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_ta=
x&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D45" title=3D"Edit section: Montenegro"><s=
pan>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></=
div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Montenegro" title=3D"Montene=
gro">Montenegro</a>, capital gains are included in taxable income and are s=
ubject to the standard 9% corporate tax rate. They are calculated in accord=
ance with the tax rules and can only be offset against capital losses.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-55" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-55"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5=
5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Morocco">Morocco</h3><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D46" title=3D"Edit section: Morocco"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Morocco" title=3D"Morocco">M=
orocco</a>, capital gains made from the sale of properties by individuals a=
re taxable with a flat tax rate of 20% of the capital gains. The taxed amou=
nt must be higher than 3% of the selling price of the property.
</p><p>An exemption from the individual income tax in the case of making ca=
pital gains by selling a property is applicable if the property is used as =
a principal residence for a duration of at least six years.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-56" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capita=
l_gains_tax#cite_note-56"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>56<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Nepal">Nepal</h3><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;acti=
on=3Dedit&amp;section=3D47" title=3D"Edit section: Nepal"><span>edit</span>=
</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nepal" title=3D"Nepal">Nepal=
</a>, Capital Gain Tax refers to gain occurred on the sale of any assets or=
 properties. Since 17 July 2021, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Government_of_Nepal" title=3D"Government of Nepal">Government of Nepal</=
a> has introduced the Long Term Tax and Short Term Tax on the gain after sa=
le of shares. For individuals, the Long Term Tax rate is 5% of the gain aft=
er deduction of brokerage and commission and the  Short Term Tax rate is 7.=
5% of the gain after deduction of brokerage and commission.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Netherlands">Netherlands</h=
3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_=
tax&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D48" title=3D"Edit section: Netherlands"=
><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span=
></div>
<p>Capital gains generally are exempt from tax. However, exceptions apply t=
o the following assets:
</p>
<ul><li>Capital gains realised on the disposal of business assets (includin=
g real estate) and on the disposal of other assets that qualify as income f=
rom independently performed activities;</li>
<li>Capital gains on liquidation of a company;</li>
<li>Capital gains derived from the sale of a substantial interest in a comp=
any (that is, 5% of the issued share capital).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-57" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#c=
ite_note-57"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>57<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
<p>Taxable income under Box 2 category includes dividends and capital gains=
 from a substantial shareholding (inkomsten uit aanmerkelijk belang) (i.e. =
a shareholding of at least 5%). Income that falls into the Box 2 category i=
s taxed at a flat rate of 25%.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-58" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-58"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>58<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup>
</p><p>Box 3: taxable income from savings and investments (viz. real estate=
). However a "theoretical capital yield" of 4% is taxed at a rate of 30% (s=
o 1.2%) but only if the savings plus stocks of a person exceed a threshold =
of 25.000 euros. This will be raised to a threshold of 30.000 euros in 2018=
, together with other changes so that people with less wealth, pay lower ta=
xes.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-59" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-59"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>59<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In general an individual will not have to pay tax on capital gains. =
So if the main residence is sold or shares are sold the profit is not taxab=
le. This is different if the transaction(s) exceed(s) normal asset manageme=
nt. In that case the capital gain is treated as income from other activitie=
s or even business income.
</p><p>Relevant are:
</p>
<ul><li>the number of transactions =E2=80=93 the more transactions the soon=
er it is assumed that activities exceed normal asset management;</li>
<li>specific knowledge of the individual =E2=80=93 if the individual is a p=
rofessional trader, the personal transactions will be seen as taxable incom=
e sooner than if the individual does not have specific knowledge or experie=
nce;</li>
<li>work which is invested in the asset =E2=80=93 if maintenance of a prope=
rty is taken care of by an external party the activities may be seen as nor=
mal asset management, if the owner does all the maintenance himself and eve=
n the renovations the tax authorities will argue that this is no longer nor=
mal asset management.</li></ul>
<p>So it depends on the actual facts and circumstances how the capital gain=
 is treated. Even judges do not always decide the same.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
60" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_ga=
ins_tax#cite_note-60"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>60<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"New_Zealand">New Zealand</h=
3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_=
tax&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D49" title=3D"Edit section: New Zealand"=
><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span=
></div>
<p>New Zealand has no capital gains tax, however income tax may be charged =
on profits from the sale of personal property and land that was acquired fo=
r the purposes of resale.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-61" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-61"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>61<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up> This tax is often avoided and not usually enforced,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
62" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_ga=
ins_tax#cite_note-62"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>62<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> perhaps due to the difficulty in proving =
intent at the time of purchase. However, there were a few cases of the IRD =
enforcing the law; in 2004 the government gathered $106.6&nbsp;million chec=
king on property sales from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Queens=
town,_New_Zealand" title=3D"Queenstown, New Zealand">Queenstown</a>, <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/W%C4%81naka" title=3D"W=C4=81naka">W=C4=
=81naka</a> and some areas of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Auck=
land" title=3D"Auckland">Auckland</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-63" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note=
-63"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>63<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup>
</p><p>Generally profits from frequent stock trading will be deemed taxable=
 income.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-64" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-64"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>64<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In a speech delivered on 3 June 2009, New Zealand Treasury Secretary=
 John Whitehead called for a capital gains tax to be included in reforms to=
 New Zealand's taxation system.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-NZ_Herald_10576312_65-0"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains=
_tax#cite_note-NZ_Herald_10576312-65"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
65<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The introduction of a cap=
ital gains tax was proposed by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/New_Zealand_Labour_Party" title=3D"New Zealand Labour Party">Labour Party<=
/a> as an election campaign strategy in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/2011_New_Zealand_general_election" title=3D"2011 New Zealand gene=
ral election">2011</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2014_Ne=
w_Zealand_general_election" title=3D"2014 New Zealand general election">201=
4 general elections</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-NZ_Herald_10738434_66-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#c=
ite_note-NZ_Herald_10738434-66"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>66<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-67" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite=
_note-67"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>67<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>On 17 May 2015, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fifth_N=
ational_Government_of_New_Zealand" title=3D"Fifth National Government of Ne=
w Zealand">Fifth National Government</a> announced it would tighten rules f=
or taxing profits on the sale of property. From 1 October 2015, any person =
selling a residential property within two years of purchase would be taxed =
on the profits at their marginal income tax rate. This is known as the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bright-line_rule#New_Zealand_%E2%80%93=
_Taxation_(Bright-line_Test_for_Residential_Land)_Act_2015" title=3D"Bright=
-line rule">bright line test</a>. The seller's main home is exempt, as well=
 as properties inherited from deceased estates or transferred as part of a =
relationship settlement. To help enforcement, all buyers need to supply the=
ir <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inland_Revenue_Department_(New_=
Zealand)" title=3D"Inland Revenue Department (New Zealand)">IRD number</a> =
at settlement.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-68" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-68"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>68<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-69" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-69"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>69<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Shortly after taking office =
in 2017, the new <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sixth_Labour_Gove=
rnment_of_New_Zealand" title=3D"Sixth Labour Government of New Zealand">Lab=
our government</a> extended the bright line test threshold first from two y=
ears to five years, and later to ten years.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-70" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite=
_note-70"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>70<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In mid-February 2019, the Labour-led Coalition government's independ=
ent <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tax_Working_Group" title=3D"Ta=
x Working Group">Tax Working Group</a> recommended implementing a capital g=
ains tax to lower the personal tax rate and to target "polluters". This pro=
posed tax would cover assets such as land, shares, investment properties, b=
usiness assets and intellectual property but would exclude family homes, ca=
rs, boats, and art. The Working Group proposed setting a top tax rate of 33=
%. The Working Group's chairman Cullen claimed that the capital gains tax w=
ould raise NZ$8.3&nbsp;billion over the next five years, which would be inv=
ested into increased social security benefits.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-71" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#c=
ite_note-71"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>71<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-72" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-72"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>72<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> In mid-April 2019, the Coalition government announced that it would not =
be implementing a capital gains tax, citing the inability of members of the=
 governing coalition to reach a consensus on capital gains taxation.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-73" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-73"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>73<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-74" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#c=
ite_note-74"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>74<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-75" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-75"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>75<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p><sup id=3D"cite_ref-76" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-76"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>76<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Norway">Norway</h3><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;ac=
tion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D50" title=3D"Edit section: Norway"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The individual capital gains tax in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Norway" title=3D"Norway">Norway</a> is 22%<sup id=3D"cite_ref-77" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#=
cite_note-77"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>77<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup> (2019). Gains from certain investment vehicles li=
ke stocks and bonds are multiplied by 1.44 before calculating tax, resultin=
g in an effective tax rate of 31.68%. In most cases, there is no capital ga=
ins tax on profits from sale of one's principal home. This tax was introduc=
ed in 2006 through a reform that eliminated the "RISK-system", which intend=
ed to avoid the double taxation of capital. The new shareholder model, intr=
oduced in 2006, aims to reduce the difference in taxation of capital and la=
bor by taxing dividends beyond a certain level as ordinary income. This mea=
ns that focus was moved from capital to individuals and their level of inco=
me. This system also introduced a deductible allowance equal to the share's=
 acquisition value times the average rate for Treasury bills with a 3-month=
 period adjusted for tax. Shielding interest shall secure financial neutral=
ity in that it returns the taxpayer what he or she alternatively would have=
 achieved in a safe, passive capital placement exempt from additional taxat=
ion. The main purpose of the allowance is to prevent adverse shifts in inve=
stment and corporate financing structure as a result of the dividend tax. A=
ccording to the papers explaining the new policy, a dividend tax without su=
ch shielding could push up the pressures on the rate of return on equity in=
vestments and lead Norwegian investors from equities to bonds, property etc=
.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Pakistan">Pakistan</h3><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&am=
p;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D51" title=3D"Edit section: Pakistan"><span>ed=
it</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Capital Gains Tax (CGT) in Pakistan is levied on the profit from selling=
 capital assets, which include property, jewelry, artwork, and collectibles=
, securities <sup id=3D"cite_ref-78" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-78"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>78<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> excludin=
g stock-in-trade, depreciable assets, and personal-use items, as defined by=
 the Income Tax Ordinance 2001.The gain is determined by subtracting the as=
set=E2=80=99s adjusted cost=E2=80=94factoring in purchase price and allowab=
le improvements=E2=80=94from the sale proceeds. Tax rates vary by asset typ=
e, holding period, and the taxpayer=E2=80=99s filing status, with, for exam=
ple, listed securities acquired on or after 1 July 2013 generally taxed at =
15%, while gains on immovable property (acquired before July 01, 2024)<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-79" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-79"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7=
9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> are subject to a sliding s=
cale that favors longer holding periods. Properties acquired after July 1, =
2024 are subject to fix rate of 15%. Assets hold for personal use or exempt=
 from Capital Gains Tax, however <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G=
old" title=3D"Gold">gold</a> along with other precious items are categorize=
d as a taxable asset in Pakistan, subject to capital gains tax under Sectio=
ns 37(5)(d) and 38(5) of the Income Tax Ordinance.<sup class=3D"noprint Inl=
ine-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:C=
itation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sour=
ces. (March 2025)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> Capital gains tax =
other than from securities, stocks and immovable properties are charged wit=
h an individual tax slabs for upto 45%.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Templat=
e Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation nee=
ded"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (March=
 2025)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>Read More: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taxation_in_Paki=
stan" title=3D"Taxation in Pakistan">Taxation in Pakistan</a>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Philippines">Philippines</h=
3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_=
tax&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D52" title=3D"Edit section: Philippines"=
><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span=
></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1305433154"><table class=3D"box-Unreferenced_section plainlinks metadata am=
box ambox-content ambox-Unreferenced" role=3D"presentation"><tbody><tr><td =
class=3D"mbox-image"><div class=3D"mbox-image-div"><span typeof=3D"mw:File"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Question_book-new.svg" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"icon" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.=
org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/60px-Question_book-new.sv=
g.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"50" height=3D"39" class=3D"mw-file-eleme=
nt" data-file-width=3D"512" data-file-height=3D"399"></a></span></div></td>=
<td class=3D"mbox-text"><div class=3D"mbox-text-span">This section <b>does =
not <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citing_sources" titl=
e=3D"Wikipedia:Citing sources">cite</a> any <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability" title=3D"Wikipedia:Verifiability">source=
s</a></b>.<span class=3D"hide-when-compact"> Please help <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:EditPage/Capital_gains_tax" title=3D"Special=
:EditPage/Capital gains tax">improve this section</a> by <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:Referencing_for_beginners" title=3D"Help:Refere=
ncing for beginners">adding citations to reliable sources</a>. Unsourced ma=
terial may be challenged and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikip=
edia:Verifiability#Burden_of_evidence" title=3D"Wikipedia:Verifiability">re=
moved</a>.</span>  <span class=3D"date-container"><i>(<span class=3D"date">=
May 2014</span>)</i></span><span class=3D"hide-when-compact"><i> (<small><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:Maintenance_template_removal" t=
itle=3D"Help:Maintenance template removal">Learn how and when to remove thi=
s message</a></small>)</i></span></div></td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>There is a 6% Capital Gains Tax and a 1.5% Documentary Stamps on the dis=
posal of real estate in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philip=
pines" title=3D"Philippines">Philippines</a>. While the Capital Gain Tax is=
 imposed on the gains presumed to have been realized by the seller from the=
 sale, exchange, or other disposition of capital assets located in the Phil=
ippines, including other forms of conditional sale, the Documentary Stamp T=
ax is imposed on documents, instruments, loan agreements and papers evidenc=
ing the acceptance, assignment, sale or transfer of an obligation, rights, =
or property incident thereto. These two taxes are imposed on the actual pri=
ce the property has been sold, or on its current Market Value, or on its Zo=
nal Value whichever is higher. Zonal valuation in the Philippines is set by=
 its tax collecting agency, the Bureau of Internal Revenue. Most often, rea=
l estate transactions in the Philippines are being sealed higher than their=
 corresponding Market and Zonal values.
As a standard process, the Capital Gain Tax is paid for by the seller, whil=
e the Documentary Stamp is paid for by the buyer. However, either of the tw=
o parties may pay both taxes depending on the agreement they entered into.
</p><p>Tax Rates:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-80" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-80"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>80<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><br>
For real property
</p>
<ul><li>6%, higher of fair market value (zonal or assessed value) and selli=
ng price</li></ul>
<p>For Shares of Stocks Not Traded in the Stock Exchange
</p>
<ul><li>15%, net of tax basis and directly attributable cost</li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Poland">Poland</h3><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;ac=
tion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D53" title=3D"Edit section: Poland"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Since 2002 there is one flat <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ta=
x_rate" title=3D"Tax rate">tax rate</a> (19%) on capital income. It include=
s: selling stocks, bonds, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mutual_f=
und" title=3D"Mutual fund">mutual funds</a> shares and also interests from =
bank <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deposit_account" title=3D"Dep=
osit account">deposits</a>. The tax was introduced by <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marek_Belka" title=3D"Marek Belka">Marek Belka</a> when=
 acting as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ministry_of_Finance=
_(Poland)" title=3D"Ministry of Finance (Poland)">Finance Minister</a> and =
therefore is informally called the "Belka tax" (<a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Polish_language" title=3D"Polish language">pl.</a> <i>podatek=
 Belki</i>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-81" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-81"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>81<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Portugal">Portugal</h3><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&am=
p;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D54" title=3D"Edit section: Portugal"><span>ed=
it</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>There is a capital gains tax on sale of home and property. Any capital g=
ain (<i>mais-valia</i>) arising is taxable as income. For residents this is=
 on a sliding scale from 12 to 40%. However, for residents the taxable gain=
 is reduced by 50%. Proven costs that have increased the value during the l=
ast five years can be deducted. For non-residents, the capital gain is taxe=
d at a uniform rate of 25%. The capital gain which arises on the sale of ow=
n homes or residences, which are the elected main residence of the taxpayer=
 or his family, is tax free if the total profit on sale is reinvested in th=
e acquisition of another home, own residence or building plot in <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Portugal" title=3D"Portugal">Portugal</a>.
</p><p>In 1986 and 1987 Portuguese corporations changed their capital struc=
ture by increasing the weight of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E=
quity_capital" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Equity capital">equity capita=
l</a>. This was particularly notorious on quoted companies. In these two ye=
ars, the government set up a large number of tax incentives to promote equi=
ty capital and to encourage the quotation on the <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Lisbon_Stock_Exchange" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Lisbon=
 Stock Exchange">Lisbon Stock Exchange</a>. Until 2010, for stock held for =
more than twelve months the capital gain was exempt. The capital gain of st=
ock held for shorter periods of time was taxable on 10%.
</p><p>From 2010 onwards, for residents, all capital gain of stock above =
=E2=82=AC500 is taxable on 20%. Investment funds, banks and corporations ar=
e exempted of capital gain tax over stock.
</p><p>As of 2013, it is 28%.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Romania">Romania</h3><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D55" title=3D"Edit section: Romania"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Romania" title=3D"Romania">R=
omania</a>, the net capital gain is subject to income tax at the flat rate =
of 10%. The taxable amount is calculated based on the difference between th=
e sale price and the acquisition price of the shares. In general, broker/tr=
ansaction fees in connection with the acquisition or sale are tax deductibl=
e.
</p><p>The individual has to report any sale of shares (i.e. capital gain/l=
oss) through the annual return by 25 May of the year following the one in w=
hich the sale was performed and pay the related taxes, based on a self-asse=
ssment made considering the information reflected in the annual return, wit=
hin the same reporting deadline (i.e. 25 May). The health insurance contrib=
ution (10%, capped) is also due if the total yearly income from capital gai=
ns, alone or together with other categories of income reaches the annual th=
reshold of 12 minimum gross salaries (30600 RON, approx. =E2=82=AC6100 as o=
f 2022).
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Russia">Russia</h3><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;ac=
tion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D56" title=3D"Edit section: Russia"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>There is no separate tax on capital gains; rather, gains or gross receip=
t from sale of assets are absorbed into income tax base.<sup class=3D"nopri=
nt Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikip=
edia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to reliabl=
e sources. (December 2009)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup><sup class=
=3D"noprint Inline-Template" style=3D"margin-left:0.1em; white-space:nowrap=
;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Please_clarify" t=
itle=3D"Wikipedia:Please clarify"><span title=3D"The text near this tag may=
 need clarification or removal of jargon. (December 2009)">clarification ne=
eded</span></a></i>]</sup> Taxation of individual and corporate taxpayers i=
s distinctly different:
</p>
<ul><li>Capital gains of individual taxpayers are tax free if the taxpayer =
owned the asset for at least three years. If not, gains on sales of real es=
tate and securities are absorbed into their personal income tax base and ta=
xed at 13% (residents) and 30% (non-residents).<sup class=3D"noprint Inline=
-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Cita=
tion needed"><span title=3D"e.g. Why would it be 13% for Russian citizens (=
apparently flat), when Russian Federation does not have a flat tax for inco=
me-tax rates? Also how would Russian Federation know the income-tax basis o=
f a foreigner? (appears that the 30%, even if correct, could not possibly b=
e correlated to or &quot;base&quot; upon to the foreigner's annual income t=
ax.) (December 2009)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> A tax resident =
is any individual residing in the Russian Federation for more than 183 days=
 in the past year.</li>
<li>Capital gains of resident corporate taxpayers operating under the <i>ge=
neral tax framework</i> are taxed as ordinary business profits at the commo=
n rate of 20%, regardless of the ownership period. Small businesses operati=
ng under the <i>simplified tax framework</i> pay tax not on capital gains, =
but on gross receipts at 6% or 15%.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dividend" title=3D"Dividend">D=
ividends</a> that may be included into gains on disposal of securities are =
taxed at source at 13% (residents) and 15% (non-residents) for either corpo=
rate or individual taxpayers.</li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Serbia">Serbia</h3><span cl=
