p>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"United_Kingdom">United King=
dom</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_=
gains_tax&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D74" title=3D"Edit section: United=
 Kingdom"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</sp=
an></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax_in=
_the_United_Kingdom" title=3D"Capital gains tax in the United Kingdom">Capi=
tal gains tax in the United Kingdom</a></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"History">History</h4><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D75" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Channon observes that one of the primary drivers to the introduction of =
CGT in the UK was the rapid growth in property values post <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_War_II" title=3D"World War II">World War II<=
/a>. This led to property developers deliberately leaving office blocks emp=
ty so that a rental income could not be established and greater capital gai=
ns made.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-96" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-96"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>96<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The capital g=
ains tax system was therefore introduced by chancellor <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Callaghan" title=3D"James Callaghan">James Calla=
ghan</a> in 1965.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-97" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-97"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>97<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Basics">Basics</h4><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;ac=
tion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D76" title=3D"Edit section: Basics"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Individuals who are residents or ordinarily residents in the United King=
dom (and trustees of various trusts), who are on the basic tax rate are sub=
ject to capital gains tax of 18% on profits from residential property, and =
10% on gains from all other chargeable assets.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-=
Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citat=
ion needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources.=
 (January 2022)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>For higher rate taxpayers, the rate is 28% on profits from residenti=
al property, and 20% on everything else.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-98" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_no=
te-98"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>98<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>There are exceptions such as for principal private residences, holdi=
ngs in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Individual_savings_account"=
 title=3D"Individual savings account">individual savings accounts</a> or <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gilts" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Gilts">gilts</a>. Certain other gains are allowed to be rolled over upo=
n re-investment. Investments in some start up enterprises are also exempt f=
rom CGT. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Entrepreneurs%27_relief" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Entrepreneurs' relief">Entrepreneurs' relief=
</a> allows a lower rate of CGT (10%) to be paid by people who have been in=
volved for a year with a trading company and have a 5% or more shareholding=
.
</p><p>Shares in companies with trading properties are eligible for <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Entrepreneurs%27_relief" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Entrepreneurs' relief">entrepreneurs' relief</a>, but not in=
vestment properties.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-99" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-99"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>99<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the 2021=E2=80=9322 tax year, taxpayers can make =C2=A312,300 in =
capital gains before they have to pay any tax =E2=80=93 and couples can poo=
l their allowance. This is the same as it was the year before.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-100" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ca=
pital_gains_tax#cite_note-100"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>100<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Corporate_notes">Corporate =
notes</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapita=
l_gains_tax&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D77" title=3D"Edit section: Corp=
orate notes"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]<=
/span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1305433154"><table class=3D"box-Update plainlinks metadata ambox ambox-cont=
ent ambox-Update" role=3D"presentation"><tbody><tr><td class=3D"mbox-image"=
><div class=3D"mbox-image-div"><span typeof=3D"mw:File"><span><img alt=3D""=
 src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/53/Ambox_cur=
rent_red_Americas.svg/60px-Ambox_current_red_Americas.svg.png" decoding=3D"=
async" width=3D"42" height=3D"34" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=
=3D"360" data-file-height=3D"290"></span></span></div></td><td class=3D"mbo=
x-text"><div class=3D"mbox-text-span">This section needs to be <b>updated</=
b>.<span class=3D"hide-when-compact"> Please help update this article to re=
flect recent events or newly available information.</span>  <span class=3D"=
date-container"><i>(<span class=3D"date">August 2018</span>)</i></span></di=
v></td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>Companies are subject to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United=
_Kingdom_corporation_tax" title=3D"United Kingdom corporation tax">corporat=
ion tax</a> on their "chargeable gains" (the amounts of which are calculate=
d along the lines of capital gains tax in the United Kingdom). Companies ca=
nnot claim taper relief, but can claim an indexation allowance to offset th=
e effect of inflation. A corporate <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Substantial_shareholdings_exemption" title=3D"Substantial shareholdings ex=
emption">substantial shareholdings exemption</a> was introduced on 1 April =
2002 for holdings of 10% or more of the shares in another company (30% or m=
ore for shares held by a life assurance company's long-term insurance fund)=
. This is effectively a form of UK <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Participation_exemption" title=3D"Participation exemption">participation e=
xemption</a>. Almost all of the corporation tax raised on chargeable gains =
is paid by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Life_assurance" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Life assurance">life assurance</a> companies taxe=
d on the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I_minus_E_basis" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"I minus E basis">I minus E basis</a>.<sup class=3D"n=
oprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"W=
ikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to rel=
iable sources. (June 2020)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>The rules governing the taxation of capital gains in the United King=
dom for individuals and companies are contained in the <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taxation_of_Chargeable_Gains_Act_1992" title=3D"Taxati=
on of Chargeable Gains Act 1992">Taxation of Chargeable Gains Act 1992</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Background_to_changes_to_18=
%_rate"><span id=3D"Background_to_changes_to_18.25_rate"></span>Background =
to changes to 18% rate</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw=
-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.p=
hp?title=3DCapital_gains_tax&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D78" title=3D"E=
dit section: Background to changes to 18% rate"><span>edit</span></a><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In the Chancellor's October 2007 Autumn Statement, draft proposals were =
announced that would change the applicable rates of CGT as of 6 April 2008.=
 Under these proposals, an individual's annual exemption will continue but =
taper relief will cease and a single rate of capital gains tax at 18% will =
be applied to chargeable gains. This new single rate would replace the indi=
vidual's marginal (Income Tax) rate of tax for CGT purposes. The changes we=
re introduced, at least in part, because the UK government felt that <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Private_equity" title=3D"Private equity"=
>private equity</a> firms were making excessive profits by benefiting from =
overly generous taper relief on business assets.<sup class=3D"noprint Inlin=
e-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Cit=
ation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable source=
s. (January 2008)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>The changes were criticised by a number of groups including the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Federation_of_Small_Businesses" title=
=3D"Federation of Small Businesses">Federation of Small Businesses</a>, who=
 claimed that the new rules would increase the CGT liability of small busin=
esses and discourage entrepreneurship in the UK.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-101" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_ta=
x#cite_note-101"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>101<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup> At the time of the proposals there was concer=
n that the changes would lead to a bulk selling of assets just before the s=
tart of the 2008=E2=80=9309 tax year to benefit from existing taper relief.=
 Capital Gains Tax rose to 28% on 23 June 2010 at 00:00.
</p><p>On 6 April 2016, new lower rates of 10% (for basic taxpayers) and 20=
% (for higher taxpayers) were introduced for non-property disposals.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-102" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-102"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1=
02<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Historical">Historical</h4>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_gains_ta=
x&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D79" title=3D"Edit section: Historical"><s=
pan>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></=
div>
<p>Individuals paid capital gains tax at their highest marginal rate of inc=
ome tax (0%, 10%, 20% or 40% in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Tax_year" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Tax year">tax year</a> 2007/8) b=
ut from 6 April 1998 were able to claim a <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/w/index.php?title=3DTaper_relief&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;redlink=3D1" c=
lass=3D"new" title=3D"Taper relief (page does not exist)">taper relief</a><=
/i> which reduced the amount of a gain that is subject to capital gains tax=
 (thus reducing the effective rate of tax) depending on whether the asset i=
s a "business asset" or a "non-business asset" and the length of the period=
 of ownership. Taper relief provided up to a 75% reduction (leaving 25% tax=
able) in taxable gains for business assets, and 40% (leaving 60% taxable), =
for non-business assets, for an individual.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-taperrelief_=
103-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital=
_gains_tax#cite_note-taperrelief-103"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
103<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Taper relief replaced in=
dexation allowance for individuals, which could still be claimed for assets=
 held prior to 6 April 1998 from the date of purchase until that date, but =
was itself abolished on 5 April 2008.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"United_States">United State=
s</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCapital_ga=
ins_tax&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D80" title=3D"Edit section: United S=
tates"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span>=
</span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Federal_Capital_Gains_Tax_Collections_1954-20=
09_history_chart.pdf" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upl=
oad.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3a/Federal_Capital_Gains_Tax_Co=
llections_1954-2009_history_chart.pdf/page1-500px-Federal_Capital_Gains_Tax=
_Collections_1954-2009_history_chart.pdf.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"5=
00" height=3D"179" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"2775" data-=
file-height=3D"995"></a><figcaption>US capital gains taxes history</figcapt=
ion></figure>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax_in=
_the_United_States" title=3D"Capital gains tax in the United States">Capita=
l gains tax in the United States</a></div>
<p>In the United States, with certain exceptions, individuals and corporati=
ons pay <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Income_tax" title=3D"Incom=
e tax">income tax</a> on the net total of all their capital gains. Short-te=
rm capital gains are taxed at a higher rate: the <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Ordinary_income" title=3D"Ordinary income">ordinary income</=
a> tax rate. The tax rate for individuals on "long-term capital gains", whi=
ch are gains on assets that have been held for over one year before being s=
old, is lower than the ordinary income tax rate, and in some tax brackets t=
here is no tax due on such gains.
</p><p>The tax rate on long-term gains was reduced in 1997 via the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taxpayer_Relief_Act_of_1997" title=3D"Tax=
payer Relief Act of 1997">Taxpayer Relief Act of 1997</a> from 28% to 20% a=
nd again in 2003, via the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jobs_and=
_Growth_Tax_Relief_Reconciliation_Act_of_2003" title=3D"Jobs and Growth Tax=
 Relief Reconciliation Act of 2003">Jobs and Growth Tax Relief Reconciliati=
on Act of 2003</a>, from 20% to 15% for individuals whose highest tax brack=
et is 15% or more, or from 10% to 5% for individuals in the lowest two inco=
me tax brackets (whose highest tax bracket is less than 15%). (See <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Progressive_tax" title=3D"Progressive tax=
">progressive tax</a>.) The reduced 15% tax rate on <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Qualified_dividends" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Quali=
fied dividends">qualified dividends</a> and capital gains, previously sched=
uled to expire in 2008, was extended through 2010 as a result of the <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tax_Increase_Prevention_and_Reconciliati=
on_Act" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Tax Increase Prevention and Reconcil=
iation Act">Tax Increase Prevention and Reconciliation Act</a> signed into =
law by President Bush on 17 May 2006, which also reduced the 5% rate to 0%.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-104" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-104"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>104<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Toward the end of =
2010, President Obama signed a law extending the reduced rate on eligible d=
ividends until the end of 2012.
</p><p>The law allows for individuals to defer capital gains taxes with tax=
 planning strategies such as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S=
tructured_sale" title=3D"Structured sale">structured sale</a> (ensured inst=
allment sale), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charitable_trust" t=
itle=3D"Charitable trust">charitable trust</a> (CRT), installment sale, <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Private_annuity_trust" title=3D"Priva=
te annuity trust">private annuity trust</a>, a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/1031_exchange" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"1031 exchange">1=
031 exchange</a>, or an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Opportunit=
y_zone" title=3D"Opportunity zone">opportunity zone</a>. The United States,=
 unlike almost all other countries, taxes its citizens (with some exception=
s)<sup id=3D"cite_ref-105" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax#cite_note-105"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>105<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> on their worldwi=
de income no matter where in the world they reside. U.S. citizens therefore=
 find it difficult to take advantage of personal <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Tax_haven" title=3D"Tax haven">tax havens</a>. Although ther=
e are some <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Offshore_bank" title=3D=
"Offshore bank">offshore bank</a> accounts that advertise as tax havens, U.=
S. law requires reporting of income from those accounts, and willful failur=
e to do so constitutes <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tax_evasion=
" title=3D"Tax evasion">tax evasion</a>.
</p>
